# Documentation

## Philosophy
- Documentation pages are **manually written**, not auto-generated.
- Use reusable documentation components for consistency.
- Prefer explicit slots over attributes for clarity.

## Structure
- Documentation pages: `resources/views/docs/components/{category}/{name}.blade.php`
- Template docs: `resources/views/docs/templates/{category}/{name}.blade.php`
- Use `<x-daisy::docs.page>` as main wrapper with sections.
- Use `<x-daisy::docs.sections.*>` components: `intro`, `example`, `variants`, `api`, `custom`.

## Components Usage
- `<x-daisy::docs.sections.example>` and `<x-daisy::docs.sections.variants>` require two explicit slots:
  - `<x-slot:preview>`: rendered component preview
  - `<x-slot:code>`: code editor with source code
- Store code in PHP variables to avoid quote escaping issues.
- Always provide both slots for complete examples.

## Commands
- `inventory:update`: refreshes the docs inventory cache and manifests used by the app
- Other docs-related commands must match the actual command signatures present in `app/Console/Commands`

## Best Practices
- Write documentation manually for full control and clarity.
- Use `DocsHelper::getComponentProps()` for API sections.
- Keep examples simple and relevant.
- Avoid code duplication between preview and code slots.
- Prefer exercising the package through its public Blade namespace and documented config, not by duplicating package source code in the docs app.

## PHPDoc Requirements
- **Mandatory** for all classes, methods, functions, and properties.
- **Required tags**: `@param` (with type), `@return` (with type), `@throws` when applicable.
- **Array shapes**: Use `@return array<int, array<string, mixed>>` for complex arrays.
- **Conciseness**: Only document rationale, invariants, edge cases. Avoid obvious descriptions.
- **No inline comments**: Prefer PHPDoc blocks over inline comments. Only use inline comments for very complex logic.
